12 / 4

Python will output 3.0.
Note that division output floats (decimals) as default, not integers.

10 % 2

Python will output 0.
 - It outputs the remainder that is left when you divide the first
   number by the second.
 - If it divides evenly, the result is 0)

2 + 2 == 4

Python will output True.
 - It determines if the equation is True or False and outputs
   that as the value.

8 // 3

Python will output 2.
 - Floor Division determines the answer and rounds down to the
   integer below that number.
 - 3 / 8 equals 2.667 which rounds down to 2.

apple = 1
apple += 1

Value of apple is now 2.

This process can be done with other operators,

Generally speaking, nearly any combination of lowercase letters, 
uppercase letters, numbers and underscores can be used for a variable 
name, but the following either must or should be avoided:
 - You cannot begin the name with a number. 
 - You cannot use operator words such as and, or & not (any word
   that changes color when you complete it).
 - Avoid package names, module names, class names and function
   names (Python may not throw an error but it will lead to problems).
 - Avoid using 'l' (lowercase el), 'I' (uppercase eye) or 'O'
   (uppercase oh) as single character variable names (the 1st and
   2nd can be confused for each other or the number 1 and the last
   can be confused for the number 0).

Most Python users snake case for naming variables. This is created 
using lowercase letters and/or numbers separated by underscores,
examples include:
 - number_of_college_graduates 
 - choice_1
variable_name\n\nEnter the name and Python will output its current value.

%whos

Python will output a table with the headings: Variable, Types and Data/Info.
 - The Data/Info column will display the value if it is an integer, float or string.
   but it will display the number of values if it is a list, set, tuple or dictionary.
 - This table is created at a point in time so its output would be different after you add a new variable
del(variable_name)\n\nNote that Python will not output an acknowledgement of deletion.

variable_name = 'Hello'

Note that the following:
 - You can use either single quotes or double quotes.
 - Any spaces in between the quotes are part of the string
   (i.e. 'Hello ')
 - Returns can be added by adding a forward-slash followed by a
   lowercase letter n.

variable_name = [5, 5.5, 'Hello']

Note that the following:
 - Lists are made with square brackets.
 - Items are separated by commas.
 - The items have a defined ordered and allow duplicate values -
   i.e. [5, 5.5, 5].
 - The items can be different data types (as they are in this example)
   or all the same data type.

variable_name = (5, 5.5, 'Hello')

Note the following:
 - Tuples are are made with parentheses.
 - Items are separated by commas.
 - The items have a defined ordered and allow duplicate values -
   i.e. (5, 5.5, 5).
 - The items can be different data types (as they are in this example)
   or all the same data type.

variable_name = {5, 5.5, 'Hello'}

Note the following:
 - Sets are are made with curly brackets.
 - Items are separated by commas.
 - The items do not have a defined ordered and duplicate values
   are not allowed.
 - The items can be different data types (as they are in this example)
   or all the same data type.

variable_name = {
     'brand': 'Ford' ,
     'model':'Mustang',
     'year': 1964
}

Note the following:
 - Dictionaries are are made with curly brackets.
 - Dictionaries store values in key:value pairs.
 - The key:value pairs do not have a defined order and do not allow
   duplicate key names (different keys can have the same value).
 - The items can be different data types (as they are in this example)
   or all the same data type.

variable_name = True

Note that the following:
 - The word (True or False) must be spelled with an uppercase
   'T' or 'F'.
 - Typically, you will establish a boolean variable in this manner
   and have it changed later if certain conditions are met.

len(string_name)

\  OR

len('string')

Python outputs the number of characters in the string.

string_name[0]

Characters in a string are indexed, starting at 0 for the first character
(so if the string is 'Hello' in our code above, Python will output 'H').
 - Note that if a string has 5 characters, the last character can be IDed in 2 ways:
   1. string_name[4]
   2. string_name[-1]

len(list_name)

\  OR

len([item1, item2, item3])

Python outputs the number of items in the list.

list_name[0]

Items in a list are indexed, starting at 0 for the first item
(so if the list is [1,2,3] in our code above, Python will output 1).
 - Note that if a list contains 5 items, the last item can be IDed in 2 ways:
   1. list_name[4]
   2. list_name[-1]

len(tuple_name)

\  OR

len((item1, item2, item3))

Python outputs the number of items in the tuple.

tuple_name[0]

Items in a tuple are indexed, starting at 0 for the first item
(so if the tuple is (1,2,3) in our code above, Python will output 1).
 - Note that if a tuple contains 5 items, the last item can be IDed in 2 ways:
   1. tuple_name[4]
   2. tuple_name[-1]

len(set_name)

\  OR

len({item1, item2, item3})

Python outputs the number of items in the set.
You cannot ID an item by location in a set as sets do not have an order
